  "prompt": "When the hydronium-ion concentration of a solution is 1\u00d710\u221212 M , what is the pH of the solution?",
  "response": "To determine the pH of a solution when given the hydronium-ion concentration (\\([H_3O^+]\\)), we use the pH formula:\n\n\\[\n\\text{pH} = -\\log [H_3O^+]\n\\]\n\nHere, the hydronium-ion concentration \\([H_3O^+]\\) is \\(1 \\times 10^{-12} \\, \\text{M}\\). Plugging this into the formula:\n\n\\[\n\\text{pH} = -\\log (1 \\times 10^{-12})\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\text{pH} = - \\log (10^{-12})\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\text{pH} = - (-12)\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\text{pH} = 12\n\\]\n\n### Final Answer:\nThe pH of the solution is **12**.",
